---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import PageLayout from "@/layouts/Base.astro";
import profile from "@/assets/profile.jpg";
---

<PageLayout meta={{ title: "Oscar Gilg" }}>
	<section class="space-y-5">
		<div class="flex flex-col-reverse items-start gap-6 sm:flex-row sm:gap-8">
			<div class="flex-1 space-y-4">
				<h1 class="title">Oscar Gilg</h1>
				<p class="leading-relaxed">
					I work on empirical AI welfare research at MATS 9.0, mentored by
					<a class="cactus-link" href="https://patrickbutlin.com/" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank"
						>Patrick Butlin</a
					>
					(<a class="cactus-link" href="https://eleosai.org/" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank"
						>Eleos AI</a
					>). I'm French-British of Italian descent, grew up in London, and have a soft spot for
					Amsterdam.
				</p>
			</div>
			<Image
				alt="Oscar Gilg"
				class="border-accent/30 aspect-square w-32 shrink-0 rounded-full border-2 object-cover shadow-sm sm:w-40"
				loading="eager"
				src={profile}
				width={400}
				widths={[160, 240, 320, 480]}
			/>
		</div>
		<p class="leading-relaxed">
			I started coding as a teenager and got into AI through a fascination with artificial minds:
			which properties of mind, if any, could be reproduced in a computer. I read
			<em>Superintelligence</em> before university and wrote about it in my personal statement.
		</p>
		<p class="leading-relaxed">
			At Oxford, ML in practice turned out to be more debugging than wonder, and I drifted toward
			probability, betting, and the conceptual machinery of trading. During Covid I picked up
			<em>Consciousness Explained</em>, then <em>From Bacteria to Bach</em>. Dennett's bottom-up
			framing, how mind-like things can be built out of mindless processes (with analogues in
			economics and biology), left a deep mark. My dissertation tried to formalise intuitions
			about consciousness in hierarchical generative models under the free energy principle,
			mostly as an intuition pump for what a mathematical theory of mind could even look like. I
			then emailed
			<a
				class="cactus-link"
				href="https://www.francoiskammerer.com/"
				rel="noreferrer"
				target="_blank">François Kammerer</a
			> because illusionism, on my reading, frames the scientific problem the right way: first explain
			why we think we are conscious, then ask whether we are. I spent a few months in Bochum trying
			to formalise theories of introspection, got somewhere, and learned that theory at this level
			is genuinely hard.
		</p>
		<p class="leading-relaxed">
			After a couple of internships at university, I followed the smartest people I knew into
			trading and joined Optiver in Amsterdam on the equity screen desk. I learned a lot from very
			smart people, picked up some Dutch, and loved the city. The work was not ultimately
			fulfilling, and when the next wave of frontier capabilities started landing I decided I
			needed to be inside it again, returning to the question that pulled me in originally:
			digital minds, and what we owe them.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="title text-accent mb-4 text-xl">Projects</h2>
		<ul class="space-y-4" role="list">
			<li>
				<div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
					<a
						class="cactus-link font-semibold"
						href="https://github.com/oscar-gilg/zombuul"
						rel="noreferrer"
						target="_blank">Zombuul</a
					>
					<span class="text-muted shrink-0 text-xs">2026</span>
				</div>
				<p class="text-muted mt-1">
					I built a Claude Code plugin for launching autonomous research agents with access to
					GPUs.
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
					<span class="font-semibold">Personas use a shared preference vector</span>
					<span class="text-muted shrink-0 text-xs">MATS 9.0, 2026</span>
				</div>
				<p class="text-muted mt-1">
					With Patrick Butlin (
					<a
						class="cactus-link"
						href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/pxC2RAeoBrvK8ivMf/models-have-linear-representations-of-what-tasks-they-like-1"
						rel="noreferrer"
						target="_blank">post</a
					>,
					<a
						class="cactus-link"
						href="https://github.com/oscar-gilg/Preferences"
						rel="noreferrer"
						target="_blank">code</a
					>; preprint forthcoming).
				</p>
			</li>
			<li>
				<div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
					<span class="font-semibold">Split Persona Training</span>
					<span class="text-muted shrink-0 text-xs">SPAR 2025</span>
				</div>
				<p class="text-muted mt-1">
					Trigger-conditioned persona fine-tuning. Under review at ICML 2026.
				</p>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="title text-accent mb-4 text-xl">CV</h2>
		<p>
			<a class="cactus-link" href="/cv.pdf" rel="noreferrer" target="_blank">View CV (PDF)</a>
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="mt-12">
		<h2 class="title text-accent mb-4 text-xl">Contact</h2>
		<ul class="list-disc space-y-1 ps-5" role="list">
			<li>
				Email:
				<span data-email-user="oscar.gilg18" data-email-domain="gmail.com"
					>oscar.gilg18 [at] gmail [dot] com</span
				>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a
					class="cactus-link"
					href="https://github.com/oscar-gilg"
					rel="noreferrer"
					target="_blank">github.com/oscar-gilg</a
				>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a
					class="cactus-link"
					href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/oscar-gilg"
					rel="noreferrer"
					target="_blank">linkedin.com/in/oscar-gilg</a
				>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</section>

	<script is:inline>
		document.querySelectorAll("[data-email-user]").forEach(function (el) {
			var u = el.getAttribute("data-email-user");
			var d = el.getAttribute("data-email-domain");
			var addr = u + "@" + d;
			var a = document.createElement("a");
			a.href = "mai" + "lto:" + addr;
			a.textContent = addr;
			a.className = "cactus-link";
			el.replaceWith(a);
		});
	</script>
</PageLayout>
